ITNPBD2 Assignment - Project Gutenberg Analysis¶

Executive Summary¶

Project Gutenberg is an open-source repository that holds notable old literature works; thus, an analysis of the works from the library would provide some insight into the trends and correlations of old literature and help to distinguish it from modern publications. A metadata of essential information was created, together with an analysis of the overall trend in book length of each book, and the ratio of book length to unique word count was the first phase of the analysis. In the second phase, a few books by a randomly chosen author were examined to determine if there were any patterns in the author's usage of vocabulary, sentiment, similarity in writing, and genre. To compare the writing styles of two authors from the same or different eras, books by different writers were reviewed as part of phase three of the analysis. This evaluation was based on the factors indicated in phase II. According to analyses, authors usually stick to their favourite genres; as an example, from our analysis, W.W. Jacob's writings skewed towards fiction, while Sir Arthur Quiller's works were poems. Additionally, there aren't any significant differences in the book's intentions and polarity of the books from same author. The target audience was also determined by analysing the book's complexity.

[PHASE I] Creating the metadata¶

A project to digitise and archive literature, including novels, poems, short tales, and plays, named Project Gutenberg, is an online library of free eBooks. It includes artistic creations created from 1800 or later. In order to comprehend the trend of literary work and gain insight into the development of literature and authors, we are analysing some of the works in the Gutenberg library and the associated data.

Three steps will be taken to complete the analysis.

  • Develop metadata to examine the relationship and trend in general information
  • Examine books by a particular author
  • Examine books from several authors

Data Cleaning and Preparations¶

The bibliographic record in [1] (a representative sample of a book from the archive) served as the inspiration for the creation of metadata for the complete collection in the repository. What if we could gather all the essential details in one location?

Glob module and open() function has been used to read all the files, and to search a specific string, the regular expression libraries were used referring [2][3], and in order for the refunction to search for the termand select the necessary phrase, each file has been searched based on the keywordthat comes prior toit, such as "Title:", 'Author:' and so on. And the total word count and unique word count were then retrieved using the split() and len() functions, which has been stored in a list later and the combined data has been put together in a dataframe to make it more readable and accessible.

Throughout the report, the following functions() will be used to open files that are meant to,

  • book_search_by_author_name(author_name) will search a book by author name.
    • In the function .txt format files will be searched in the current directoryusing the os.getcwd() method. Once the.txt files are searched, it will scan for the authors name,and if it is present, the file name will be returned, which will be used in subsequent stages to search a keyword in the data files.
  • open_book_by_file_name(book_num) will Read a book where the file name itself serves as the book number argument.
    • The book is searched and opened using the open() function and read by the readlines() method, which is converted to an array, and the irrelevant introduction and licencing information will be removed using the del() function to make the text less cluttered and prepare for our research. After the lines are deleted, each item is concatenated and converted back to a single string for further analysis.

def book_search_by_author_name(author_name):
    here = os.getcwd()
    for file in os.listdir(here):
        if file.endswith('.txt'):
            read_file = open(here + "/" + file, 'r')
            if author_name in read_file.read():
                keyword_list = list_to_numpy_array(file)
                print(keyword_list, end=' ')


def open_book_by_file_name(book_num):
    with open(f'{book_num}.txt', 'r') as fid:
        lines = fid.readlines()
        del lines[:7]
        del lines[-400:]
        del lines[8:14]
        text_in_string = ' '.join([i for i in lines])
        return text_in_string

Data Cleaning and Preparations¶

The sections will clean and process the text data using the functions() listed below. Using the aforementioned function open_book_by_file_name();it will read the book and alter the text's case withlower() method andsearch for the keyword "http" to replace the hyperlinks with a blank space using regular expressions, create sentence tokens and a list of word tokens using nltk tokenization, and thereafter remove all stop words as the final step in the process to capture precise data. The article [8] has beenreferredfor learning about eliminating stopwords, and [9] has been referredfor learning about the isalpha() method, which will aid in keeping alphabetic characters and deleting unnecessary characters, making the procedure less tedious. Finally, the lists were transformed into a NumPyarray to provide a compact and efficient result to be used in the future.

In [24]:
def cleaned_data(book_num):
    # removed hyperlinks
    remove_hyperlink = re.sub(r'http\S+', '', open_book_by_file_name(book_num), flags=re.MULTILINE)
    # converted to lowercase text
    lowercase_text = remove_hyperlink.lower()
    # The words would, could are replaced to avoid any complication in following steps
    clean_text = lowercase_text.replace(':', ' ').replace(',', ' ').replace('?', ' ').replace('!', ' ').replace('*',
                                                                                                                '').replace(
        '-', ' ').replace('.', ' ').replace(';', ' ').replace("''", ' ').replace("``", ' ').replace(":", ' ').replace(
        "'s", " ").replace('would', " ").replace('could', ' ')
    return clean_text


def sentence_tokens(book_num):
    # sentence tokenization
    token_sentence = nltk.sent_tokenize(cleaned_data(book_num))
    token_sentence_array = list_to_numpy_array(token_sentence)
    return token_sentence_array


def word_tokens(book_num):
    # word tokenization
    token_word = nltk.word_tokenize(cleaned_data(book_num))
    words_list = [x for x in token_word if x.isalpha()]
    words_list_array = list_to_numpy_array(words_list)
    return words_list_array


def remove_stopwords(word_tokens_list):
    # remove stopwords using nltk stopwords
    processed_token_words = [x for x in word_tokens_list if x not in stopwords.words('english')]
    processed_token_words_array = list_to_numpy_array(processed_token_words)
    return processed_token_words_array

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The consol_book_data() function will print the cleaned data as astring, sentence and word tokens, and the tokens after stopword removal; and the function consol_book_features(), will return the word counts, lexical diversity, frequently used keywords, and frequently occured bigrams in a dictionary, which will aid in the analysis of the data in subsequent stages. The cleaned data is not kept in any variables to reduce clutter and further complexity, however for readability, each data cleaning process has been printed in the subsequent phases.

The len() function counts the total words to produce the book length from the cleaned text string; the total word count has been gathered by counting the word tokens, and set() will store the unique words, which were later tallied. The frequently occurring words and word pairs have been identified using FreqDist() function.

In [25]:
def consol_book_data(book_num):
    print(f'The data after inital cleaning:\n {cleaned_data(book_num)[:45]}', '\n')
    print(f'After Sentence tokenization:\n {sentence_tokens(book_num)[0][:25]}', '\n')
    print(f'Tokenized words:\n {word_tokens(book_num)[:25]}', '\n')
    word_tokens_list_1 = word_tokens(book_num)
    print(f'After removing stopwords:\n {remove_stopwords(word_tokens_list_1)[:10]}', '\n\n')


def consol_book_features(book_num):
    word_tokens_list_1 = word_tokens(book_num)
    book_length = len(cleaned_data(book_num))
    total_words_count = len(remove_stopwords(word_tokens_list_1))
    unique_words_count = len(set(remove_stopwords(word_tokens_list_1)))
    lex_div = unique_words_count / total_words_count
    f_dist = FreqDist(remove_stopwords(word_tokens_list_1))
    freq_bigrams = FreqDist(list(nltk.bigrams(remove_stopwords(word_tokens_list_1))))
    
    dict_of_book_features = {'book length': book_length, 'word count': total_words_count,
                            'unique word count': unique_words_count, 'lexical diversity': lex_div,
                            'frequent words': f_dist, 'frequent bigrams': freq_bigrams}
    return dict_of_book_features

def pos_tag(book_num):
    pos_tagged_words = nltk.pos_tag(word_tokens(book_num))
    pos_tag_to_array = list_to_numpy_array(pos_tagged_words)
    return pos_tag_to_array

Q5 - Evaluating the complexity of the literature will be a fascinating aspect of the analysis, as it could contribute to a better understanding of people, experiences and culture in the author's era.¶

Lexical density (the ratio of phrases to the total word count) reveals the text's complexity since it indicates whether it is appropriate for a specificlanguage and demonstrates how complex the text is as it uses more nouns and phrases to expressspecificmeaning. As a result, knowing that a book is short, its lexical density will help us determine its complexity as well. The lexical density has been determined by comparing the fraction of pos-tagged words to the overall number of words in the book.

In [33]:
def lex_density(book_num):
    pos_count = len(pos_tag(book_num))
    lex_density_value = (pos_count/consol_book_features(book_num)['book length'])*100
    return lex_density_value

def sentiment_polarity_score(book_num):

Q7 - Earlier, we were able to analyse the frequently used words and attempt to determine their relationship. Is it also possible to find textual similarities in the author's books?¶

The text similarity will give us information about how similarly an author writes his books, which may be used to anticipate the theme of the next book they will publish and the target audience, and also reveal how similarly authors write. Referring package spacy [6][7], I have performed a corpus-based text similarity assessment in the analysis. To check for similarity, the text string has been called as aspacy nlp object, which has been called at the start of the aanalysis. The pos tagging will be applied to the NLP object of the string. The words classified as a verb, noun, or adjectives will be selected using .pos and lemmatizedwith .lemma to obtainthe root word, which will then be converted back to a string and analyzed for text similarity. To further explore the parallels based on them, we have gathered nouns, verbs, and adjectives. Below is a graphical representation of the combined results.

In [39]:
def get_noun(data):
    book_noun = " ".join([word.lemma_ for word in data if word.pos_ == 'NOUN'])
    return nlp(book_noun)


def get_verb(data):
    book_verb = " ".join([word.lemma_ for word in data if word.pos_ == 'VERB'])
    return nlp(book_verb)


def get_adj(data):
    book_adj = " ".join([word.lemma_ for word in data if word.pos_ == 'ADJ'])
    return nlp(book_adj)

The Numpy array has been converted to string in the following section to feed in the nlp object of spacy, as spacy doesnt accept NumPy array numpy.str and was getting the typeerror, "TypeError: Argument 'string' has incorrect type (expected str, got numpy.str)"

Relative to book 4, which is a mystery thriller, as we discovered through earlier research, book 5 is less complicated. In comparison to a thriller, the fifth book appears to be a poem.

Q6 continued - Can we identify and compare the sentiment score and emotions in the book written by different authors?¶

The sentiment score, which was addressed in Part II, offers us a broad picture of how favourable or unfavourable the book's context is. Emotions, on the other hand, are a factor that influences how profound and significant the writing turnsout to be and contributesin creating a connection between the writer and their readers. Therefore, it is essentialto compare the sentiment score as well as emotion scores of different authors in order to comprehend their variances. The functions of sentiment analysis has been used to evaluate the polarity score.

The Text2emotion package has been referred to in [5], and the te.get emotion() function will identify emotion from each word that has been extracted from thepre-processed text and graded based on the emotions that are contained in the module. The emotion analysis demonstrates the narrator's representational quality of their point of view, which could reveal the story's element, language, and tone, as well as aid in identifying emotional differences between works and distinguishing literature from different parts of the world. In order to prevent any complications, 20,000 words near the end of each book have been set aside for the analysis, however it can be performed on the whole text obtaining same results.

Q7 continued - Finding out how different authors' text similarities turn out might be intriguing.¶

The authors Wadsworth Camp, W.W Jacobs, and Arthur Quiller-Couch must have different writing styles and genres, comparing and analysing the similarities between the three must provide some insight into their writing style. As inphase II-A, the spacy NLPlibrary has been employed and same functions has been used to find the similarity in the texts.

The similarity score between books by two distinct authors is relatively outstanding, being 0.893 between books 2 & 5, but only 0.95 between books 4 & 5, showing a change in genre and writing style. When comparing books 2, 4, and 5, books 4 & 5 are more comparable than books 2 & 5, suggesting that the books may share more descriptions and phrases. The similarity score between the nouns used in Books 2 & 5 also reveals the genre of the work because there is a clear distinction between the vocabulary used in fiction and poetry. Additionally, it demonstrates that when comparing books 2 and 5, the verb and adjective scores appear to be distinct, whereas the text similarity score is close to the noun similarity.

These numerical values aid in comparing the literature works and, at a better elevation, can be used to train the data further in a machine-learning model rather than actual textual data.

Suggestions¶

  • The writing style, characters, narrative, and context of the books in our dataset (which are from the Victorian or Edwardian era) from the span 1800s to the early 1900s, can be utilized to shed light on how literature has changed through the time. The actual publishing date is dispersed across the data, making it difficult to sort, which inhibits our ability to analyse the data based on time. Consequently, the dateutil.parser module or more sophisticated algorithms may be employed to search for the book's actual year of publication to achieve the aforementioned findings.

  • Apart from analysing old literature and the evolution of literature evaluation, data from our analysis may be applied tomore recent works, which can be used to further develop a model that predicts the topics of the author's future books. The topics can be predicted using algorithms like Support Vector Machine (SVM), which excels in categorical data analysis and pattern recognition.

  • Furthermore, as readers tend to select a particular genre, book length, author of the book they have read before, and so on, our evaluations can also be modified to a predictor to predict a book's sales before its publication, if additional information, such as the publisher, price, previous sales of the books, and the month the book was sold, is presented along with our data. The future success or failure of the book's sales can be predicted by using logistic regression, which divides data into the classifications of (0) or (1) based on multiple predictor variables. In addition, Random Forest can be used to forecast asale's success or failure because it uses multiple trees and selects the majorityas the best value, producing the optimal result. Additionally, the article [11] has specifics about a statistical model developed to recognise and forecast a pattern in book sales, that can be incorporated intoour booksales prediction.
